observations.recommendation:
We recommended and management agreed that:
a) The Municipal Accounting Office to prepare the necessary adjusting entries to set up the liability account for the 15 per cent and record the July-December 2023 5 per cent collections from building fees and other charges;
b) The Municipal Treasury Office and Municipal Accounting Office to prepare a separate account for the 15 per cent share of building permit fees and other charges, and maintain a separate Trust Fund or Trust Liability account;
c) The Building Official prepare a Program of Work detailing the manner of utilization of the 15 per cent share to be held under trust, to be approved by the Local Chief Executive, and to be submitted to the DPWH Secretary thru the NCBDO;
d) The Municipal Treasury Office remits the 5 per cent DPWH Share; and
e) Henceforth, comply with the provisions of Presidential Decree (PD) No. 1096 and DILG and DPWH Joint Memorandum Circular (JMC) No. 001 relative to the accounting and remittance of building permit fee collections.

We recommended that the:
a) Liquidating officer must be provided with a safety vault to secure funds in her possession awaiting Deposit;
b) Collectors always secure the acknowledgment/signature of the LO on their Reports of Collections and Deposits (RCDs) and indicate the cash remittances on the space provided. The Liquidating Officer (LO) shall receive and sign all RCDs and verify the actual cash remittances received with what was indicated by the collector in the RCDs;
c) Liquidating officer be proficient in recording the collection remitted and deposits in the LO Cash book to avoid errors and unrecorded remittances and for easier monitoring;
d) Liquidating Officer strictly adheres to Section 28 of COA Circular No. 92-382 to deposit intact all his collections, as well as all collections turned over to him by the collectors/tellers, with the authorized depository bank daily or not later than the next banking day; and
e) OIC Municipal Treasurer strictly monitors the remittances of collections by the collector and deposits made by the Liquidating Officer to avoid accumulation of material amounts for a considerable period in the possession of any accountable officer.

7.4 We recommended that management:
 prepare and post the citizen’s charter for procurement process as required under Memorandum Circular 2019-002 to guide other concerned offices and clients for the procedures to be followed;
 adhere to the time frame indicated in its Citizen’s Charter to ensure efficient delivery of its services.

 the Municipal Accountant reconcile the records of fund transfers and make necessary adjustments, if any;
 Management enforce liquidation from Implementing Agencies by requiring submission of approved Fund Utilization Report and/or immediate refund of any unused balance; and
 stop granting additional assistance (in the form of fund transfers) to LGUs and NGAs with unliquidated balance/s unless prior settlement thereof is made.

 monitor and demand timely submission of liquidation reports and/or immediate refund of any unused balances;
 stop granting additional cash advances to Officials and Employees, unless settlement is made on previous cash advances. Relative to this, require the Municipal Accountant to include as a supporting document to the grant of cash advances, a certification that previous cash advance/s were liquidated or that the grantee has no unliquidated cash advance.
 issue demand letters to require Officials and Employees with due and demandable cash advances to immediately settle their accounts, otherwise a Notice of Disallowance shall be issued.

 Provide all rooms of slaughterhouse with at least two (2) refuse receptacles or containers made of impervious materials, one for biodegradable and one for non-biodegradable wastes;
 Provide the slaughterhouse with sufficient number of water proof metal containers with tight fitting metal cover for holding trimming hair, inedible animal parts and other similar wastes;
 Provide the slaughterhouse containers for holding various condemned parts and organs plainly marked “Condemned for Animal Food”, or “Condemned for Incineration”, or “Condemned for Rendering”. All these wastes shall be disposed daily;
 Henceforth, conform to the pertinent provisions of the Code on Sanitation of the Philippines (PD 856) on the operations of the LGUs slaughterhouse.

 Call the attention of the concerned personnel on the proper waste management, especially on waste segregation;
 Conduct information drive on the prohibition on open dumping and burning;
 Schedule collection of garbage in the Birthing Homes and Slaughterhouse;

We recommended that the Municipal Accountant:
a. submit schedules to support the balances of the accounts in the financial statements and maintain subsidiary ledgers for all real and nominal accounts to facilitate verification;
c. coordinate with the Municipal Treasurer to establish and properly document transactions pertaining to Cash-Local Treasury and Petty Cash Funds.
